[{"id":40260,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$C=4 \\mu F$","$C=8 \\mu F$","$C=1 \\mu F$","$C=2 \\mu F$"],"answer":2,"solution":"$f=\\frac{1}{2 \\pi \\sqrt{L C}}$\n$C=\\frac{1}{4 \\times \\pi^2 f^2 \\times 10}$\n$C=1 \\mu F$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":40237,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>275</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Wb</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>200</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Wb</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>225</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Wb</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>250</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>Wb</mi></math>"],"answer":3,"solution":"<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">E</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">f</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>i</mi><mi>R</mi><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#981;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>i</mi><mi>R</mi></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8747;</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#981;</mi></mrow></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mo>&#8747;</mo><mstyle mathvariant=\"italic\"><mrow><mo>(</mo><mi>i</mi><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow></mstyle><mi>R</mi></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>q</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">&#916;</mi><mi>&#981;</mi></mrow><mi>R</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mtext>&#160;Area&#160;under</mtext><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>i</mi><mo>-</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>graph</mtext></math><br /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mo>&#8710;</mo><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced><mrow><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mn>2</mn></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mn>250</mn><mi>&#160;</mi><mi>Wb</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2017 (02 Apr)","image":null},{"id":40200,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["parallel to the plane of coil and increasing with time","outward and increasing with time","outward and decreasing with time","parallel to the plane of coil and decreasing with time"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>Lenz&#39;s&nbsp;law state that the direction of the induced current is such that it opposes its cause of generation, so,&nbsp;</p><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/f06837a1-9753-4b36-b74c-b777081d41fc-image.png\" style=\"width: 180px; height: 196px;\" /><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mover><mi>B</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover></math>,&nbsp;must not be parallel to the plane of coil for non-zero flux and according to Lenz&#39;s&nbsp;law if <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math> is outward it should be decreasing for anticlockwise induced current.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (31 Aug Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40235,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$0.17 \\mathrm{~A}$","$0.15 \\mathrm{~A}$","$0.34 \\mathrm{~A}$","$0.25 \\mathrm{~A}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"Given: Capacitance, $C=0.2 \\mu \\mathrm{F}=0.2 \\times 10^{-6}$ $\\mathrm{F}$\nInductance $\\mathrm{L}=0.5 \\mathrm{mH}=0.5 \\times 10^{-3} \\mathrm{H}$\nCurrent $\\mathrm{I}$ = ?\nUsing energy conservation\n$$\n\\frac{1}{2} C V^2=\\frac{1}{2} C V_1^2+\\frac{1}{2} L I^2\n$$\n$\\frac{1}{2} \\times 0.2 \\times 10^{-6} \\times 10^2+0$\n$=\\frac{1}{2} \\times 0.2 \\times 10^{-6} \\times 5^2+\\frac{1}{2} \\times 0.5 \\times 10^{-3} I^2$\n$\\therefore \\quad I=\\sqrt{3} \\times 10^{-1} \\mathrm{~A}=0.17 \\mathrm{~A}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2018 (15 Apr Shift 1 Online)","image":null},{"id":40170,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/2def0a13-3d1b-440e-a579-ff591554c058.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 174px;\" /></p><p>It is given that the current is varying sinusoidally. The current can be written as&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>I</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>sin</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi></math>.</p><p>The magnetic field through the solenoid&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>n</mi><mi>I</mi></math></p><p>The flux through the square is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>n</mi><mi>I</mi><mi>A</mi></math></p><p>The emf is</p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#949;</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>n</mi><mi>A</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>d</mi><mo>(</mo><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>sin</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi><mo>)</mo></mrow><mrow><mi>d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#949;</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>n</mi><mi>A</mi><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>cos</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><mi>t</mi></math></p><p>The amplitude of the emf is,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#949;</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>n</mi><mi>A</mi><msub><mi>I</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>&#969;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mn>50</mn><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>700</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#949;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>44</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (10 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40178,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>Maximum value of induced EMF can be written as,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#958;</mi><mi>max</mi></msub><mo>=</mo><mi>N</mi><mi>A</mi><mi>B</mi><mi>&#969;</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>14</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>3</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>360</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow><mn>60</mn></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>1584</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (30 Jan Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40253,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$6 e^{-5 t} V$","$\\frac{12}{t} e^{-3 t} V$","$6\\left(1-e^{-t / 0.2}\\right) V$","$12 e^{-5 t} V$"],"answer":3,"solution":"$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{I}_1=\\frac{\\mathrm{F}}{\\mathrm{R}_1}=\\frac{12}{2}=6 \\mathrm{~A} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{E}=\\mathrm{L} \\frac{\\mathrm{dl_{2 }}}{\\mathrm{dt}}+\\mathrm{R}_2 \\times \\mathrm{I}_2 \\\\\n& \\mathrm{I}_2=\\mathrm{I}_0\\left(1-\\mathrm{e}^{-\\mathrm{t} / \\mathrm{t}_{\\mathrm{c}}}\\right) \\Rightarrow \\mathrm{I}_{\\mathrm{o}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{E}}{\\mathrm{R}_2}=\\frac{12}{2}=6 \\mathrm{~A} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{t}_{\\mathrm{c}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{L}}{\\mathrm{R}}=\\frac{400 \\times 10^{-3}}{2}=0.2 \\\\\n& \\mathrm{I}_2=6\\left(1-\\mathrm{e}^{-\\mathrm{t} / 0.2}\\right)\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\nPotential drop across $L=E-R_2 l_2=12-2 \\times 6\\left(1-e^{-b t}\\right)=12 e^{-5 t}$\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/ZYOu7dEZgHrmJ8UwaY3fMFFCDsYoIxPFkYXeC8CigA4.original.fullsize.png\"><br>\nDirections: Question numbers 28,29 and 30 are based on the following paragraph. Two moles of helium gas are taken over the cycle $A B C D A$, as shown in the $P-T$ diagram.<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/hYJgZD1CUxcvMjKC5LEXEnhRUUQTP_zw_bTTNv7u9e4.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2009","image":null},{"id":40251,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$\\mathrm{I}_1=-\\mathrm{I}_2=\\frac{\\mathrm{B} \\ell \\mathrm{v}}{\\mathrm{R}}, \\mathrm{I}=\\frac{2 \\mathrm{~B} \\ell \\mathrm{v}}{\\mathrm{R}}$","$\\mathrm{I}_1=\\mathrm{I}_2=\\frac{\\mathrm{B} \\ell \\mathrm{v}}{3 \\mathrm{R}}, \\mathrm{I}=\\frac{2 \\mathrm{~B} \\ell \\mathrm{v}}{3 \\mathrm{R}}$","$l_1=I_2=I=\\frac{B \\ell v}{R}$","$I_1=I_2=\\frac{B \\ell v}{6 R}, I=\\frac{B \\ell v}{3 R}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"A moving conductor is equivalent to a battery of emf $=\\mathrm{v} \\mathrm{B} \\ell \\quad$ (motion emf)\nEquivalent circuit\n$$\n\\mathrm{I}=\\mathrm{l}_1+\\mathrm{l}_2\n$$\napplying Kirchoff's law\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& \\mathrm{I}_1 R+I R-v B \\ell=0 \\\\\n& \\mathrm{I}_2 R+I R-v B \\ell=0\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\nadding (1) \\& (2)\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n& 2 \\mathrm{IR}+\\mathrm{IR}=2 \\mathrm{vB} \\ell \\\\\n& \\mathrm{I}=\\frac{2 \\mathrm{vB} \\ell}{3 \\mathrm{R}} \\\\\n& \\mathrm{I}_1=\\mathrm{I}_2=\\frac{\\mathrm{vB} \\ell}{3 \\mathrm{R}}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$\n<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/pUPjsjy75K1skV7dpyzQKQNVetAfCge7PX6GHTWQouE.original.fullsize.png\"><br>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2010","image":null},{"id":40249,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["development of air current when the plate is placed.","induction of electrical charge on the plate","shielding of magnetic lines of force as aluminium is a paramagnetic material.","electromagnetic induction in the aluminium plate giving rise to electromagnetic damping."],"answer":3,"solution":"Oscillating coil produces time variable magnetic field. It cause eddy current in the aluminium plate which causes anti-torque on the coil, due to which is stops.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2012 (Offline)","image":null},{"id":40136,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$5.7 \\times 10^{-2}$","$7.5 \\times 10^{-2}$","$7.5 \\times 10^{-3}$","$5.7 \\times 10^{-3}$"],"answer":2,"solution":"Given: $l = 1$ m, $B = 0.10$ T, $R = 2$ Ω, $v = 1.5$ m/s<br>Motional EMF: $\\varepsilon = Blv = 0.10 \\times 1 \\times 1.5 = 0.15$ V<br>Current: $I = \\frac{\\varepsilon}{R} = \\frac{0.15}{2} = 0.075$ A<br>Magnetic force on rod: $F = BIl = 0.10 \\times 0.075 \\times 1 = 7.5 \\times 10^{-3}$ N<br>For constant velocity, applied force equals magnetic force.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (21 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40259,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$0.05 \\mathrm{~s}$","$0.1 \\mathrm{~s}$","$0.15 \\mathrm{~s}$","$0.3 \\mathrm{~s}$"],"answer":1,"solution":"$\\mathrm{I}=\\mathrm{I}_{\\circ}\\left(1-\\mathrm{e}^{-\\frac{\\mathrm{R}}{\\mathrm{L}}\\mathrm{t}}\\right)$\n$0.693=\\frac{\\mathrm{R}}{\\mathrm{L}} \\mathrm{t}$\n$\\mathrm{t}=\\frac{.3 \\times 0.693}{2}=0.1 \\mathrm{sec}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2005","image":null},{"id":40192,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msub></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mn>1</mn><mi>M</mi></mfrac></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>M</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mi>M</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>M</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/cd0f0ba9-33d5-4c16-821c-892cef71d0ca-image.png\" style=\"width: 230px; height: 101px;\" /></p><p>Here self inductances are in series&nbsp;but their mutual inductances are linked oppositely.</p><p>As the inductors connected are in series opposition, hence magnetic flux will be opposing each other. Therefore,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>L</mi><mrow><mi>e</mi><mi>q</mi></mrow></msub><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>+</mo><msub><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></msub><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn><mi>M</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (26 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40131,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$E = B\\omega A \\sin\\omega t$<br>$15.4 \\times 10^{-3} = \\dfrac{1}{2} \\times 100 \\times \\dfrac{22}{7} r^2 \\times \\dfrac{1}{2}$<br>$r = \\sqrt{\\dfrac{15.4 \\times 28 \\times 10^{-5}}{22}}$<br>$R = 14 \\text{ mm}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (22 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40241,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$400 \\mathrm{mV}$","$200 \\mathrm{mV}$","$4 \\mathrm{mV}$","$0.4 \\mathrm{mV}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"Given: No. of turns $N=1000$\nFace area, $A=4 \\mathrm{~cm}^2=4 \\times 10^{-4} \\mathrm{~m}^2$\nChange in magnetic field,\n$$\n\\Delta \\mathrm{B}=10^{-2} \\mathrm{wbm}^{-2}\n$$\nTime taken, $t=0.01 \\mathrm{~s}=10^{-2} \\mathrm{sec}$\nEmf induced in the coil $e=$ ?\nApplying formula,\nInduced emf, $e=\\frac{-d \\phi}{d t}$\n$$\n\\begin{aligned}\n&=N\\left(\\frac{\\Delta B}{\\Delta t}\\right) A \\cos \\theta \\\\\n&=\\frac{1000 \\times 10^{-2} \\times 4 \\times 10^{-4}}{10^{-2}}=400 \\mathrm{mV}\n\\end{aligned}\n$$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2014 (11 Apr Online)","image":null},{"id":40156,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p><img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/8c04d83b-14ba-451a-8567-e05d119ed428.png\" style=\"width: 200px; height: 215px;\"/></p><p>Flux linkage for inner loop</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>ϕ</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mi>B</mi><mi>center</mi></msub><mo>×</mo><msup><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>×</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>μ</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>i</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><mstyle displaystyle=\"true\"><mfrac><mi>L</mi><mn>2</mn></mfrac></mstyle></mrow></mfrac><mfenced><mrow><mi>sin</mi><mn>45</mn><mo>°</mo><mo>+</mo><mi>sin</mi><mn>45</mn><mo>°</mo></mrow></mfenced><msup><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>⇒</mo><mi>ϕ</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>μ</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>i</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>π</mi><mi>L</mi></mrow></mfrac><msup><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></math></p><p>Therefore, mutual inductance will be</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>M</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>ϕ</mi><mi>i</mi></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><msub><mi>μ</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><msup><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mrow><mi>π</mi><mi>L</mi></mrow></mfrac><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mfrac><msub><mi>μ</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi></mfrac><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>8</mn><msqrt><mn>2</mn></msqrt><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msqrt><mn>128</mn></msqrt><mo>×</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup><mo> </mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math></p><p>Hence, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>128</mn></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (31 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40184,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>emf</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mi>mV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>emf</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mi>mV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>emf</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn><mi>mV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mtext>emf</mtext><mo>=</mo><mn>5</mn><mi>mV</mi></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"<p>Given:&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>at</mtext><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#38;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>, at <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>5</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math>.</p><p>Magnetic field will decrease linearly as given below. We can say, value of magnetic field at&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mtext>will&#160;be</mtext><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn></math>.</p><p><img alt=\"\" src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/435e5f2f-d67d-4ffc-8792-8dbf3a9aea8d-9884753.png\" style=\"width: 300px; height: 245px;\" /></p><p>Therefore,</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>&#949;</mi><mtext>ind&#160;</mtext></msub><mo>=</mo><mfenced close=\"|\" open=\"|\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>&#981;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfenced close=\"|\" open=\"|\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#916;</mi><mfenced><mrow><mi>B</mi><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mi>A</mi><mfenced close=\"|\" open=\"|\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>&#916;</mi><mfenced><mi>B</mi></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mi>&#916;</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mfenced><mfrac><mn>10</mn><msqrt><mi>&#960;</mi></msqrt></mfrac></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>25</mn></mrow></mfrac></mfenced></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>1</mn></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">V</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mV</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (24 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40127,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["13.2","1.32","8.25","6.6"],"answer":1,"solution":"Circular loop with radius $r = 0.07$ m in magnetic field $B = 0.2$ T.<br>Initial flux through circular loop: $\\Phi_1 = B \\times \\pi r^2 = 0.2 \\times \\pi(0.07)^2 = 0.000980\\pi$ Wb<br>The loop is converted to a square maintaining the same perimeter: $C = 2\\pi r = 0.14\\pi$ m<br>Side of square: $a = \\frac{0.14\\pi}{4} = 0.035\\pi$ m<br>Final flux through square loop: $\\Phi_2 = B \\times a^2 = 0.2 \\times (0.035\\pi)^2 = 0.2 \\times 0.001225\\pi^2$ Wb<br>Evaluating: $\\Phi_1 = 0.2 \\times 0.0154 = 0.00308$ Wb<br>$\\Phi_2 = 0.2 \\times 0.001225 \\times 9.87 = 0.00242$ Wb<br>Change in flux: $\\Delta\\Phi = 0.00308 - 0.00242 = 0.00066$ Wb<br>Average EMF: $\\varepsilon = \\frac{\\Delta\\Phi}{\\Delta t} = \\frac{0.00066}{0.5} = 0.00132$ V $= 1.32$ mV","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40128,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["$20 \\sqrt{10}$","$0.2 \\sqrt{10}$","$200 \\sqrt{10}$","$2 \\sqrt{10}$"],"answer":0,"solution":"For a conducting wire falling in a magnetic field, induced EMF is: $\\mathcal{E} = BLv$<br>After falling through height $h = 200$ m, velocity: $v = \\sqrt{2gh} = \\sqrt{2 \\times 10 \\times 200} = \\sqrt{4000} = 20\\sqrt{10}$ m/s<br>Converting magnetic field: $B = 0.5$ Gauss $= 0.5 \\times 10^{-4}$ T<br>Induced EMF: $\\mathcal{E} = (0.5 \\times 10^{-4}) \\times 20 \\times 20\\sqrt{10} = 200 \\times 10^{-4}\\sqrt{10} = 0.02\\sqrt{10}$ V $= 20\\sqrt{10}$ mV","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2026 (23 January Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40191,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["Doubled","The same","Quadrupled","Halved"],"answer":1,"solution":"\\(\\mathrm{P}=\\frac{\\varepsilon^2}{R}\\)\r\nwhere, \\(\\varepsilon=\\) inducedemf \\(=-\\frac{d \\phi}{d t}\\)\r\n\\(\\phi=\\mathrm{NBA}\\)\r\n\\(\\varepsilon=\\mathrm{NA} \\frac{\\mathrm{dB}}{\\mathrm{dt}}\\)\r\nalso, \\(R \\propto \\frac{1}{\\mathrm{r}^2}\\)\r\nwhere, \\(\\mathrm{R}=\\) resistance and \\(\\mathrm{r}=\\) radius of wire\r\n\\(\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{P} \\propto \\frac{\\mathrm{N}^2 \\mathrm{r}^2}{\\mathrm{H}^2} \\\\ & \\frac{\\mathrm{P}_1}{\\mathrm{P}_2}=1 \\\\ & \\mathrm{P}_1=\\mathrm{P}_2 \\end{aligned}\\)\r\nThis means if the number of turns were quadrupled and the wire radius halved, the electrical power dissipated would be remains same.","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2022 (28 Jun Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40264,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["the rates at which currents are changing in the two coils","relative position and orientation of the two coils","the materials of the wires of the coils.","the currents in the two coils"],"answer":1,"solution":"No Solution Available","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2003","image":null},{"id":40199,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msup><mn>10</mn><mn>2</mn></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>"],"answer":2,"solution":"<p>The EMF&nbsp;is induced in the coil when it is moving&nbsp;in a uniform magnetic field,<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>e</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>v</mi><mi>l</mi></math>&nbsp;and the current,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>i</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mi>e</mi><mi>R</mi></mfrac></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mfrac><mrow><mi>B</mi><mi>l</mi><mi>v</mi></mrow><mi>R</mi></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>002</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>v</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>002</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>R</mi></mrow><mrow><mi>B</mi><mi>l</mi></mrow></mfrac></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>002</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mo>+</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>5</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup></math>.</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (01 Sep Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40149,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"$\\begin{aligned} & \\mathrm{I}=3 \\mathrm{t}+8 \\\\ & \\varepsilon=12 \\mathrm{mV} \\\\ & |\\varepsilon|=\\mathrm{L}\\left|\\frac{\\mathrm{dI}}{\\mathrm{dt}}\\right| \\\\ & 12=\\mathrm{L} \\times 3 \\\\ & \\mathrm{~L}=4 \\mathrm{mH}\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (05 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40162,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>The data given is&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#969;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>210</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>&#960;</mi></mrow><mn>60</mn></mfrac><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>rad</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>7</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>rad</mi><mo>&#160;</mo><msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>1</mn></mrow></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi>l</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">T</mi></math></p><p>The emf is given by</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#949;</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>B</mi><mi>&#969;</mi><msup><mi>l</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>7</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>2</mn></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>88</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mV</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (15 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40225,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["<math><mi> </mi><mn>1000</mn></math>","<math><mn>5000</mn></math>","<math><mn>10000</mn></math>","<math><mn>50000</mn></math>"],"answer":1,"solution":"Equation of motion for slider: <br/><math><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">i</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></math>  <br/><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>+</mo><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">v</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mo>⇒</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>.</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>  <br/>Comparing with <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>.</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>+</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>  <br/><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mo>;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi><mo>=</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi></math>  <br/>We know: <math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow><mrow><mfrac><mrow><mo>-</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">b</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow></msup></math>  <br/>For amplitude to be <math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><mo>/</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>,</mo></math>  <br/><math><msub><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>0</mn></mrow></msub><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">A</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>⇒</mo><mfrac><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>×</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn></math>  <br/><math><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">t</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">R</mi></mrow><mrow><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">B</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup><msup><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">l</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>10,000</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">c</mi></math>  <br/>Time period = <math><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">π</mi><msqrt><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">m</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">k</mi></mrow></mfrac></msqrt><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mi mathvariant=\"normal\"> </mi><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">s</mi></math>  <br/>Number of oscillations = <math><mfrac><mrow><mn>10,000</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mn>5,000</mn></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (08 Apr Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40230,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>12</mn><mo>&#xA0;</mo><mi>mV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>1</mn><mo>&#xA0;</mo><mi>mV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>2</mn><mo>&#xA0;</mo><mi>mV</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>6</mn><mo>&#xA0;</mo><mi>mV</mi></math>"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>emf developed is given by,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>Bvl</mi></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8756;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>=</mo><mtext>0.1</mtext><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>6</mn><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"></mspace><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">e</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup><mo>=</mo><mn>12</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mV</mi></math></p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2019 (10 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40181,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<p>According to the Faraday&#39;s law of electromagnetic induction, the emf induced in a conducting loop is given by,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>e</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>&#981;</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></math>, here,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>t</mi></math>&nbsp;is time and&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>A</mi></math>&nbsp;is magnetic flux.</p><p>Here,&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>e</mi><mo>=</mo><mfenced close=\"|\" open=\"|\"><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>&#981;</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></mfenced><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>B</mi><mi>A</mi></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mfenced><mrow><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>B</mi><mi>&#960;</mi><mfenced><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>r</mi><mfrac><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>r</mi></mrow><mrow><mo>d</mo><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac></mrow></mfenced><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>=</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>8</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>2</mn></mrow></msup></math></p><p>&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8776;</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>mV</mi></math>&nbsp;(rounded off)</p>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (29 Jan Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40208,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math>&mdash;Flux, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math>&mdash;Power dissipated, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>C</mi></math>&mdash;EMF","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math>&mdash;Power dissipated, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math>&mdash;Flux, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>C</mi><mo>&#8212;</mo><mi>E</mi><mi>M</mi><mi>F</mi></math>","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math>&mdash;Flux, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>&#8212;</mo><mi>E</mi><mi>M</mi><mi>F</mi></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>C</mi></math>&mdash;Power dissipated","<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi><mo>&#8212;</mo><mi>E</mi><mi>M</mi><mi>F</mi></math>, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math>&mdash;Power dissipated, <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>C</mi></math>&mdash;Flux"],"answer":2,"solution":"As rod moves in field area increases upto <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>b</mi></math>,&nbsp;then field is absent and again flux is generated on return journey from <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mi>b</mi></math> to <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>x</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>0</mn></math>. Thus plot <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>A</mi></math> for flux.<br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>e</mi><mo>=</mo><mo>-</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>&#981;</mi></mrow><mrow><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">d</mi><mi>t</mi></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#8658;</mo></math> curve <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi></math> for <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>emf</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo></math> Power dissipated <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mi>v</mi><mi>i</mi><mo>&#8658;</mo></math> curve <math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>C</mi></math> for power dissipated","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2021 (20 Jul Shift 1)","image":null},{"id":40151,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<img src=\"https://.app/pyq/jee_main/pY5NTwDivYJtX6CHaY0E8FN4ZcowSiTO_6MYgFE6tPk.original.fullsize.png\"><br />$\\begin{aligned} & \\because \\mathrm{V}_0-\\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{A}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{B} \\omega \\ell^2}{2} \\\\ & \\mathrm{~V}_0-\\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{B}}=\\frac{\\mathrm{B} \\omega \\ell^2}{2} \\\\ & \\therefore \\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{A}}=\\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{B}} \\therefore \\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{A}}-\\mathrm{V}_{\\mathrm{B}}=0\\end{aligned}$","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2024 (04 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40174,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<blockquote><p>Let the magnetic field of the&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mn>200</mn></math>&nbsp;turns be&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>1</mn></msub></math>. The formula of magnetic field is given by&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>B</mi><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>i</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mi>r</mi></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>Let&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>r</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>1000</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>. Thus,&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>n</mi><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>I</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>200</mn><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>I</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></mfrac></math></p><p>The flux through the&nbsp;coil of radius&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><msub><mi>r</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mo>=</mo><mn>1</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>cm</mi></math>&nbsp;is&nbsp;<math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfenced><mrow><mover><mi>B</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover><mo>&#183;</mo><mover><mi>A</mi><mo>&#8594;</mo></mover></mrow></mfenced></math><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msub><mi>B</mi><mn>1</mn></msub><mi>&#960;</mi><msub><msup><mi>r</mi><mn>2</mn></msup><mn>1</mn></msub></math></p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>&#8658;</mo><mi>&#981;</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>200</mn><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub><mi>I</mi></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup></math>&nbsp;</p><p><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>200</mn><msub><mi>&#956;</mi><mn>0</mn></msub></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mfrac><mrow><mn>200</mn><mfenced><mrow><mn>4</mn><mi>&#960;</mi><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>7</mn></mrow></msup></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>2</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><mn>10</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><mi>&#960;</mi><msup><mfenced><mrow><mn>0</mn><mo>.</mo><mn>01</mn></mrow></mfenced><mn>2</mn></msup><mspace linebreak=\"newline\"/><mo>=</mo><mn>4</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mn>10</mn><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>8</mn></mrow></msup><mo>&#160;</mo><mi mathvariant=\"normal\">H</mi></math></p></blockquote>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2023 (06 Apr Shift 2)","image":null},{"id":40217,"subject":"Physics","chapter":"Electromagnetic Induction","question":"","options":["A","B","C","D"],"answer":0,"solution":"<math><mn>100</mn><mo>=</mo><mfrac><mrow><mi>L</mi><mfenced separators=\"|\"><mrow><mn>0.25</mn></mrow></mfenced></mrow><mrow><mn>0.025</mn></mrow></mfrac><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mn>3</mn></mrow></msup></math><br /><math><mo>&#8756;</mo><mi></mi><mi></mi><mi></mi><mi></mi><mi></mi><mi></mi><mi></mi><mi></mi><mi>L</mi><mo>=</mo><mn>100</mn><mo>&#215;</mo><msup><mrow><mn>10</mn></mrow><mrow><mo>-</mo><mn>4</mn></mrow></msup><mi>H</mi></math><br /><math xmlns=\"http://www.w3.org/1998/Math/MathML\"><mo>=</mo><mn>10</mn><mo>&#160;</mo><mi>m</mi><mi>H</mi></math>","type":"mcq","source":"JEE Main 2020 (09 Jan Shift 1)","image":null}]